<body>
  <h1 class="CASENAME"><span class="RespondentName">MATHEWS, PAMELA VINEY</span><br />
  <span class="dbno">01-DB-066</span>, <span class="dbno">02-DB-014</span> &amp; <span class="dbno">02-DB-015</span>
  (<span class="Date">11/05/2003</span>) <span class="Sanction">Disbarment</span></h1>

  <p class="HEADINGSTYLE">LOUISIANA ATTORNEY DISCIPLINARY BOARD</p>

  <p class="HEADINGSTYLE">IN RE PAMELA VINEY MATHEWS</p>

  <p class="HEADINGSTYLE">NUMBERS 01-DB-066 C/W 02- DB-014 C/W 02-DB-015</p>

  <p class="HEADINGSTYLE">RECOMMENDATION TO THE LOUISIANA SUPREME COURT</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">This is a disciplinary proceeding based upon formal charges filed by the Office of Disciplinary
  Counsel (herein "ODC") against Pamela Viney Mathews<a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1" class="fn" id="_ftnref1">[1]</a>
  (herein "Respondent") of Lake Charles, Louisiana.  This matter came before the Board on nine counts of misconduct
  involving neglect of and failure to communicate with two clients, failure to return unearned fees, failure to return
  a client's file, failure to respond to eight disciplinary complaints, failure to appear pursuant to eight subpoenas
  and failure to cooperate with eight disciplinary investigations.  The Board recommends Respondent be disbarred.</p>

  <h2>PROCEDURAL HISTORY</h2>

  <h3>01-DB-066:</h3>

  <p class="Bodycopy">On June 28, 2001, ODC filed formal charges against Respondent.  The formal charges were sent by
  certified mail to Respondent's primary and secondary registration statement addresses as well as a third address. 
  All were returned as unable to deliver as addressed or forwarding time expired.  Pursuant to Rule XIX, Sections 8(c)
  and 13(a), Respondent was served with the formal charges.<a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2" class="fn"
  id="_ftnref2">[2]</a></p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">Respondent failed to answer the formal charges and the factual allegations contained in the
  formal charges were deemed admitted and proven by clear and convincing evidence on March 22, 2002.  Respondent, who
  was given twenty days, did not move to recall the order.<a href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3" class="fn"
  id="_ftnref3">[3]</a>On May 13, 2002, ODC filed an affidavit of an ODC investigator, confirming personal delivery of
  the formal charges to Respondent on April 13, 2002, at her home address, 3001 Meadowlark, Lake Charles,
  Louisiana.<a href="#_ftn4" name="_ftnref4" class="fn" id="_ftnref4">[4]</a>The parties were given until June 4, 2002,
  to file written arguments and documentary evidence on the issue of sanctions.  On October 11, 2002, ODC filed its
  Memorandum and Submission, without reference to case law, and recommended a "period of suspension".  Respondent filed
  nothing.</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">On February 26, 2003, Hearing Committee #18 (herein "Committee #18") recommended an
  eighteen-month suspension.  Neither party responded to Committee #18's report.</p>

  <h3>02-DB-014:</h3>

  <p class="Bodycopy">On February 13, 2002, ODC filed formal charges against Respondent.  The formal charges were sent
  by certified mail to Respondent's primary and secondary registration statement addresses as well as a third address. 
  All were returned as unable to deliver as addressed or forwarding time expired.  Pursuant to Rule XIX, Sections 8(c)
  and 13(a), Respondent was served with the formal charges.<a href="#_ftn5" name="_ftnref5" class="fn"
  id="_ftnref5">[5]</a>On May 13, 2002, ODC filed into the record an affidavit of an ODC investigator, confirming
  personal delivery of the formal charges to Respondent on April 13, 2002, at her home on 3001 Meadowlark, Lake
  Charles, Louisiana.</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">Respondent failed to answer the formal charges and the factual allegations contained in the
  formal charges were deemed admitted and proven by clear and convincing evidence on July 24, 2002.  Respondent, who
  was given twenty days, did not move to recall the order.<a href="#_ftn6" name="_ftnref6" class="fn"
  id="_ftnref6">[6]</a>The parties were given until October 1, 2002, to file written arguments and documentary evidence
  on the issue of sanctions.  On October 9, 2002, ODC filed its Memorandum and Submission, without reference to case
  law, and recommended a "substantial period of suspension".  Respondent filed nothing.</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">On February 10, 2003, Hearing Committee #22 (herein "Committee #22") recommended a two-year
  suspension, to run consecutively with any other suspension, with thirteen months of conditional probation with a
  practice monitor and the attendance of Ethics School.  ODC filed a Notice of No Objection to Committee #22's report. 
  Respondent did not file a response to Committee #22's report.</p>

  <h3>02-DB-015:</h3>

  <p class="Bodycopy">On February 13, 2002, ODC filed formal charges against Respondent.  The formal charges were sent
  by certified mail to Respondent's primary and secondary registration statement addresses as well as a third address. 
  All were returned as unable to deliver as addressed or forwarding time expired.  Pursuant to Rule XIX, Sections 8(c)
  and 13(a), Respondent was served with the formal charges.<a href="#_ftn7" name="_ftnref7" class="fn"
  id="_ftnref7">[7]</a>On May 13, 2002, ODC filed an affidavit of an ODC investigator, confirming personal delivery of
  the formal charges to Respondent on April 13, 2002, at her home on 3001 Meadowlark, Lake Charles, Louisiana.</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">Respondent failed to answer the formal charges and the factual allegations contained in the
  formal charges were deemed admitted and proven by clear and convincing evidence on July 12, 2002.  Respondent, who
  was given twenty days, did not move to recall the order.<a href="#_ftn8" name="_ftnref8" class="fn"
  id="_ftnref8">[8]</a>The parties were given until October 1, 2002, to file written arguments and documentary evidence
  on the issue of sanctions.  On October 9, 2002, ODC filed its Memorandum and Submission, without reference to case
  law, and recommended a "substantial period of suspension".  Respondent filed nothing.</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">On February 10, 2003, Hearing Committee #7 (herein "Committee #7") recommended a fifteen-month
  suspension, to run consecutively with her eighteen-month suspension from <span class="CITE"><i>In re Mathews,</i>
  02-1377 (La. 9/20/02); <a href="../SC/2002-09-20_2002-1377.htm">827 So.2d 1129</a></span>, restitution to her client
  and two years of supervised probation upon reinstatement.  ODC filed a Notice of No Objection to Committee #7's
  report.  Respondent did not respond to Committee #7's report.</p>

  <h3>Consolidated Cases:  01-DB-066 C/W 02- DB-014 C/W 02-DB-015:</h3>

  <p class="Bodycopy">Between February and March of 2003, the Board scheduled the cases to be heard together on April
  24, 2003.  On April 15, 2003, ODC moved to consolidate 01-DB-066, 02-DB-014 and 02-DB-015 and Judy Y. Barrasso, Panel
  "A" Chair, subsequently granted the motion.  Panel "A" heard these matters on April 24, 2003.  ODC appeared and
  recommended Respondent be suspended for three years or disbarred.  Respondent did not appear.</p>

